text: I'm John Harwood with the New York Times
in CNBC post-election praise for Barack
Obama is the reverse image of the
criticism John Kerry received after
losing the presidential election four
years ago but Kerry campaign aides
couldn't help noticing a surprise in the
returns in the battleground state of
Ohio where Kerry lost the presidency to
George W Bush the 2.7 4 million votes he
received almost precisely matched
Obama's 2008 total Obama won because
John McCain received 300 thousand fewer
votes than Bush did that's a cautionary
reminder for Obama and his team the
election turned partly on what they did
right but also on what Republicans did
wrong and there's no assurance Democrats
next time will get to run against the
Republican Party with such big problems
as former Democratic National Chairman
Don Fowler of South Carolina told me we
should be confident but not cocky
Obama's victory was impressive for any
Democrat much less the first
african-american nominee in American
history
his 52 percent share of the popular vote
exceeded that of any Democratic
candidate since Lyndon Johnson in 1964
and even topped Ronald Reagan's 1980
majority against Jimmy Carter but the
record shattering turnout that some
observers predicted appears not to have
materialized Curtis Ganz of the
committee for the Study of the American
electorate ascribes that shortfall in
part to diminished Republican enthusiasm
a demobilization that created openings
for Obama's discipline team there are
several explanations for that
conservatives never felt deep affection
for John McCain swing voters decided his
running mate Sarah Palin wasn't
qualified to be President
their appeals to cultural populism in
the homestretch drove well-educated high
income voters toward the democrats and
chaos among congressional Republicans
over the financial bailout compounded
the injuries Republicans suffered
throughout Bush's second term to their
reputation for pragmatism and competence
Democratic veterans warned against
assuming the party can repeat its 2008
success against a reinvigorated
Republican opposition as Harold Ickes a
former aide in Bill Clinton's White
House put it the lease on the office
space is likely very short Clinton's
experience highlights the risks mistakes
in his first
to White House years helped pave the way
for Newt Gingrich's Republican
revolution that al stood Democrats from
control of Congress I'm John Harwood
chief Washington correspondent for CNBC
